[1]
Date: Tue 30 Sep 2003
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Health Canada, West Nile Virus Surveillance Data, Tue 30 Sep 2003
[edited]
<http://www.hc-sc.gc.ca/pphb-dgspsp/wnv-vwn/index.html>

West Nile Virus Surveillance Data as of Tue 30 Sep 2003
-------------------------------------------------------
Human - cumulative data
-----------------------
As of Tue 30 Sep 2003 there have been a total of 1059 probable or confirmed
cases of human infection in Canada and 7 deaths (an increase of 317 cases
and 3 deaths since Mon 22 Sep 2003). Saskatchewan remains the most severely
affected province with 621 probable or confirmed cases (and 3 deaths)
followed by Alberta with 224 probable or confirmed cases (increases of 203
and 41 respectively):
Province/No. probable cases/No. confirmed cases/No. of deaths/
Nova Scotia / 0 / 1* / 0 /
Quebec /12 / 2 / 0 /
Ontario / 66 / 1* / 2** /
Manitoba / 108 / 8/ 2 /
Saskatchewan / 603 / 18 / 3 /
Alberta / 196 / 28 / 0
British Columbia 14* / 1* / 0 /
Yukon 1* / 0 / 0 /
Total 1000 / 59 / 7
*Linked to travel outside of province
** 2 probable cases; death due to other causes
[The probable cases in British Columbia and Yukon, and the confirmed cases
in Nova Scotia and Ontario, are considered to be travel-related and not
indigenous cases. Since the last update on Mon 22 Sep 2003 the number of
probable or confirmed cases has increased from 742 to 1059. Most of the new
cases occurred in Saskatchewan (203) and Alberta (41). In all, 79.8 percent
(845/1059) of the cases have occurred in the prairie provinces of
Saskatchewan and Alberta.
In 2002, there were 416 probable or confirmed cases of human West Nile
virus infection in Canada and 21 deaths attributed to the virus. All the
deaths and most of the cases occurred in Ontario and Quebec, in contrast to
the situation in 2003 when few cases have been reported from Ontario and
Quebec, and overall considerably fewer fatalities. - Mod.CP]
Equines - cumulative data
-------------------------
As of Mon 30 Sep 2003, 411 presumptive or confirmed equine cases have been
reported; Quebec (7), Ontario (42), Manitoba (53), Saskatchewan (154),
Alberta (155).
[The number of presumptive or confirmed equine cases of West Nile virus
infection has increased by 99 since Mon 22 Sep 2003. There have been no
extensions of range. - Mod.CP]
Mosquitoes - cumulative data
----------------------------
As of Tue 30 Sep 2003, 491 pools of mosquitoes have tested positive; Quebec
(80), Ontario (87), Manitoba (259), Saskatchewan (34, Alberta (31).
[This represents an increase of 37 West Nile virus-positive mosquito pools
since Mon 22 Sep 2003. In contrast to the data for other animals, the
greatest number of West Nile virus-positive mosquito pools was found in the
province of Manitoba (52.7 percent), whereas relatively few were found in
Saskatchewan (6.9 percent) and Alberta (6.3 percent). There have been no
extensions of range. - Mod.CP]
Wild Birds - cumulative data
----------------------------
As of Mon 30 Sep 2003, the following test results by province have been
reported:
Province/ No. submitted for testing/ No.tested/ No. confirmed positive /
Newfoundland and Labrador/ 69 / 64/ 0 /
Prince Edward Island/ 262 / 243 / 0 /
Nova Scotia/ 868 / 814 / 9 /
New Brunswick/ 844/ 780 / 6 /
Quebec/ 2472 / 2341 / 625 /
Ontario*/ 1680 / 1452 / 227 /
Manitoba/ 923 / 825 / 132 /
Saskatchewan/ 1196 / 956 / 157 /
Alberta/ 1500 / 1483 / 232 /
British Columbia/ 1887 / 1858 / 0/
Yukon/ 14 / 13/ 0 /
Northwest Territories/ 23/ 21 / 0 /
Nunavut/ 2/ 2 / 0 /
*Note that in the Ontario count; after the 4th confirmed positive bird, no
further testing is carried out and the birds are listed as presumed positive.
[The totals for Canada for 2003 so far are 11 740 birds submitted for
testing, 10 852 birds tested, and 1223 confirmed West Nile virus-positive.
In addition there were 3631 sightings of dead birds. This represents an
increase of 332 birds tested and 165 more birds confirmed West Nile
virus-positive; with most of the new virus-positive birds reported from the
central provinces of Quebec, Ontario and Manitoba). There has been no
extension of range. - Mod.CP]
