[2]
Date: Wed 24 Sep 2003
From: Sylvia Macbean <s.macbean@sasktel.net>
Source: The Leader-Post (Regina), Wed 24 Sep 2003 [edited]

Saskatchewan: West Nile Virus Infection Death Toll Now 6
--------------------------------------------------
Health officials in Saskatchewan reported on Tue 23 Sep 2003 that 3 more
deaths have been linked to the West Nile virus infection, bringing the
total number of deaths to 6.
The Cypress Health Region in southwestern Saskatchewan confirmed that a
woman in her 50s died in hospital Sunday from neurological complications
from the virus. "The complications related to West Nile virus infection
were what led to her death, although she had other underlying medical
conditions that contributed to the severity of her illness," said Dr.
Shauna Hudson, acting medical health officer for the Cypress Health Region.
West Nile virus has also been associated with 2 recent deaths in the Five
Hills (Moose Jaw area) Health Region this past week, said Hudson, who is
also the acting medical health officer for the region. On Friday a man in
his 70s died in hospital from complications associated with West Nile
neurological syndrome. The 2nd victim, a man in his 80s who was suffering
from West Nile fever, died in hospital Saturday from a respiratory
condition. West Nile virus was not the immediate cause of his death, but
was considered a contributing factor, Hudson said.
Earlier in September 2003, health officials reported West Nile was linked
to the deaths of 2 elderly men in the Regina Qu'Appelle Health Region and
another man in the Heartland (Rosetown area) Health Region. Dr. Eric Young,
Saskatchewan's deputy medical health officer, explained the number of
deaths in Saskatchewan is proportionate to the number of West Nile fever
and neurological syndrome cases being reported in the province. "You would
expect out of whatever number of cases any particular province or state has
of West Nile neurological syndrome a mortality rate of around 10
percent. So we have 43 cases of West Nile neurological syndrome -- 42
probable and one confirmed. So 6 out of 43 is about 14 percent, which is
just above 10 per cent, but because we are dealing with smaller numbers you
can get wider variations," Young said.
As of Tue 23 Sep 2003, the province was reporting a total of 509 probable
or confirmed human cases within the province. Of these, 164 cases have been
identified in the Five Hills Health Region.
Additional human cases are expected throughout the province as blood
samples taken in late August and early September 2003 continue to be tested
and reports are returned from physicians, Hudson said. "The risk of
infection with West Nile virus has declined dramatically since the
beginning of September, with the cooler weather resulting in lower numbers
of mosquitoes. However, people should continue to take preventative
measures -- use insect repellents, wear long pants, long-sleeved shirts,
and hats, especially on warm days," Hudson said.
[Byline: Anne Kyle]
--
Sylvia Macbean
<s.macbean@sasktel.net>
[The 3 deaths in this press report of Wed 24 Sep 2003 are additional to the
most recent surveillance data compiled by Health Canada, as of Tue 30 Sep
2003 (see [1] above), possibly because the deaths could be attributed to
other ailments. - Mod.CP]
